00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:08.590
So Stonewall was set up in
1989, in response to Section 28.

00:03:08.590 --> 00:03:10.690
And Section 28 was a
piece of legislation

00:03:10.690 --> 00:03:14.320
that prevented the promotion
of homosexuality in schools.

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:17.290
It came at a time where
culturally Britain

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:20.870
was in quite a complex place
about sexual orientation.

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:22.660
And I think it's
worth just pausing

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:25.570
and going back to what we've
been celebrating this week.

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:30.190
Fifty years ago, gay men were
persecuted, actively imprisoned

00:03:30.190 --> 00:03:31.360
for who they loved.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:33.659
And we talk a lot about love,
more on that in a moment.

00:03:33.659 --> 00:03:35.200
But actually for
what they were doing

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:37.330
quite a lot of the
time in toilets,

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:40.630
but also for who they loved,
and were persecuted and told

00:03:40.630 --> 00:03:42.700
that who they were was illegal.

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:44.920
So there are
generations of older men

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:47.617
now, men who have sex
with men, gay men, who

00:03:47.617 --> 00:03:49.450
were told that what
they were was completely

00:03:49.450 --> 00:03:52.060
illegal and unlawful.

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:54.730
In around the 1970s,
what we were seeing

00:03:54.730 --> 00:03:56.950
was that transgender
people were pretty much

00:03:56.950 --> 00:04:00.940
able to fully transition
to their desired gender

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:02.680
without much fuss
from the state.

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:05.500
So if you're rich enough,
if you're confident enough,

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:07.000
you could pretty
much transition.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.250
That changed when
a woman attempted

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:12.247
to get a better settlement
for divorcing her husband,

00:04:12.247 --> 00:04:14.830
and the high court judge ruled
that their marriage was invalid

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:16.720
because she wasn't
really a woman.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:18.519
And thus, every
informal mechanism

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:22.150
that existed for trans
people faded away.

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:25.480
In the 70s, things started
to seem to be changing.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:26.950
We had more civil
rights movements,

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:27.910
more things happening.

00:04:27.910 --> 00:04:29.470
But then HIV hit.

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:32.980
And what we saw was a
significant decimation

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:35.470
of the lesbian
and gay community.

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:38.650
And men were dying,
absolutely just dying.

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:40.660
And the state didn't respond.

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:45.250
The state did not respond
to this absolutely national

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:46.510
traumatic event.

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:49.030
And it was lesbians
running clinics

00:04:49.030 --> 00:04:51.070
with gay men, who
were running clinics

00:04:51.070 --> 00:04:55.450
for HIV positive from South
Africa, HIV positive women, HIV

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:56.080
drug dealers.

00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:58.480
You know, there was
a much greater sense

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:01.480
of a community and desperation.

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:03.310
Section 28 then came in.

00:05:03.310 --> 00:05:05.822
So section 28 came in
when I was seven years old

00:05:05.822 --> 00:05:06.655
and I was at school.

00:05:06.655 --> 00:05:10.630
And Section 28 was the
kind of third big bit

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:13.660
of rubbish to hit a
community that was already

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:15.850
feeling pretty rubbish.

00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:18.580
And I just give that
context, because that's quite

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:20.800
a hard core legacy.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:25.060
For any young LGBT kid growing
up, they know that legacy,

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:26.860
they know that history.

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:31.300
When I went to school, we didn't
talk about gay stuff at all.

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:35.860
I realized I was different
when I was about 12,

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:36.970
which is very young.

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:38.860
It's even young in
these terms really.

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:40.400
But I was always a tomboy.

00:05:40.400 --> 00:05:44.710
I was always different,
a bit other, a bit odd.

00:05:44.710 --> 00:05:46.050
I was never very cool.

00:05:46.050 --> 00:05:47.590
And never really fitted in.

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:50.530
I didn't really, and I still
don't, like small talk.

00:05:50.530 --> 00:05:55.090
I find the banality of talking
unnecessary nonsense deeply

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:55.780
frustrating.

00:05:55.780 --> 00:05:57.863
That doesn't make me a
particularly good lobbyist,

00:05:57.863 --> 00:06:00.140
more on that later.

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:04.270
So I was always a bit queer,
a bit different, a bit other.

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:06.710
When I was 12, I
realized I was gay.

00:06:06.710 --> 00:06:08.830
And I went to Cardiff Library.

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:10.130
I was brought up in Cardiff.

00:06:10.130 --> 00:06:13.120
And I read "The
Well of Loneliness,"

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:14.620
and "Orange is not
the only Fruit,"

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:17.770
because those are the two
books on the lesbian section.

00:06:17.770 --> 00:06:21.181
Now, if you know anything
about lesbian fiction,

00:06:21.181 --> 00:06:22.680
"The Well of
Loneliness" and "Orange

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:25.060
is not the only Fruit,"
the single most depressing,

00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:27.850
soul destroying books
in the entire world--

00:06:27.850 --> 00:06:31.910
they are really not top 10 tips
on how to meet a girlfriend

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:32.780
and kiss her.

00:06:32.780 --> 00:06:35.710
It's a bit more
hardcore than that.

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:38.020
So "Well of Loneliness"
doesn't end well.

00:06:38.020 --> 00:06:40.120
"Orange is not the
only Fruit" gave me

00:06:40.120 --> 00:06:42.250
a love of Jeanette
Winterson, and gave me

00:06:42.250 --> 00:06:46.630
a language and a narrative of
how to do dating from 15 to 22,

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:48.910
that meant most of my
adolescent relationships

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:52.900
were really intense and full
of very, very good constructed

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:55.130
sentences, but not a lot of fun.

00:06:55.130 --> 00:06:57.260
So Cardiff was pretty harsh.

00:06:57.260 --> 00:07:02.860
And my parents were
desperately, desperately keen

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:05.650
that I didn't let myself down.

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:08.320
So they had come from
nontraditional backgrounds.

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:10.400
My mum had trained
to be a nurse at 18.

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:11.380
Then she was a midwife.

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:12.880
Then she did a PGCE.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:14.290
Then she did an MSC.

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:17.110
Then she did her PhD when
the second child was coming.

00:07:17.110 --> 00:07:18.340
And then--

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:21.069
And so she was a teacher
in [INAUDIBLE],, and very,

00:07:21.069 --> 00:07:22.360
very pleased to have got there.

00:07:22.360 --> 00:07:23.770
But if she'd had a
different education,

00:07:23.770 --> 00:07:25.000
she could have been a doctor.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.580
That was her whole,
and is her whole story.

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:31.025
If she hadn't been one of five
children who was the girl,

00:07:31.025 --> 00:07:32.650
and made to bring up
her four brothers,

00:07:32.650 --> 00:07:33.970
she could have been a doctor.

00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:36.300
That was absolutely
how she saw it.

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:38.290
And my dad-- and I
think that's true.

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:40.306
And my dad dropped
out of school.

00:07:40.306 --> 00:07:41.680
And he trained to
be an architect

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:46.090
by working as a jobbing
lad in different shops.

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:49.025
So they done good, and they
had money, not that much money,

00:07:49.025 --> 00:07:49.900
but they'd done good.

00:07:49.900 --> 00:07:53.500
But they did not want their
kids to in any way not

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:54.730
have the most opportunity.

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:57.970
So me and my brother we just
had to work really, really hard.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.340
And it didn't really
matter what we did,

00:08:00.340 --> 00:08:02.380
as long as we
worked really hard.

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:05.140
So when my parents learned
that I was different,

00:08:05.140 --> 00:08:08.220
and was coming out,
they were so frightened.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:10.840
They were so frightened
that I would experience

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:12.220
huge levels of discrimination.

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.170
That I wouldn't get
into university.

00:08:14.170 --> 00:08:16.336
That I would struggle, that
I would really struggle.

00:08:16.336 --> 00:08:20.050
Their fear was absolutely
palpable and contagious.

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:22.300
Section 28 didn't help that.

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:24.710
The lack of visibility of
lesbian, gay, and bisexual,

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:27.100
and trans issues on
television didn't help that.

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:29.530
The lack of employers
talking about these things

00:08:29.530 --> 00:08:30.820
didn't help that.

00:08:30.820 --> 00:08:32.797
The fact that midwives
were being trained then

00:08:32.797 --> 00:08:34.630
and didn't even talk
about lesbian parenting

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:35.338
didn't help that.

00:08:35.338 --> 00:08:38.919
That absence, even
if it was neutral,

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:42.669
was deeply damaging to two
people who were just scared.

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:49.780
And I, being assertive,
clear, teenager-ee

00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:51.115
was just like, well, I am gay.

00:08:51.115 --> 00:08:52.240
Have you done anything gay?

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:52.980
No, but I am.

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:55.300
I read "Well of Loneliness."

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:57.970
So I was kind of
much more defiant

00:08:57.970 --> 00:08:59.630
than I probably
should have been.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:02.350
And what I see now with
Stonewall's youth work

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:05.170
is they're much more relaxed
about where they might end up

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:05.870
on that journey.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:07.661
And I probably would
have been more relaxed

00:09:07.661 --> 00:09:10.840
had I been growing up now.

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:12.184
So a real tension.

00:09:12.184 --> 00:09:14.350
And Stonewall was kind of
just forming and Stonewall

00:09:14.350 --> 00:09:14.960
in those days.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.480
It was a [INAUDIBLE]
organization,

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:19.240
lobbying and campaigning.

00:09:19.240 --> 00:09:20.857
At 16, I moved to Birmingham.

00:09:20.857 --> 00:09:23.440
Now when you move to Birmingham
from a small Welsh school that

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:25.990
was mainly boys, and you
know that you're gay,

00:09:25.990 --> 00:09:30.280
Birmingham has the potential
to be quite a high risk taking

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:33.540
period in one's life, I think.

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:34.960
And I really enjoyed Birmingham.

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:36.520
I also started
writing for something

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:39.280
called "Diva Magazine," which
is a magazine for lesbians.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:41.260
And in those days, I
was getting 400 pounds

00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:44.040
a month check sent to me.

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:47.110
And that so much money
when I was basically on 15

00:09:47.110 --> 00:09:49.897
quid a week, you know
paper round or something.

00:09:49.897 --> 00:09:51.730
So I was getting these
checks for 400 pounds

00:09:51.730 --> 00:09:54.340
and putting it into my instant
savers Abbey National Bank

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:55.390
account.

00:09:55.390 --> 00:09:56.690
And my mom found it.

00:09:56.690 --> 00:09:58.740
She goes why-- she thought
I was dealing drugs,

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:02.670
because I had all this money and
didn't have much to do with it.

00:10:02.670 --> 00:10:05.040
So I had this big blow
up with my parents,

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:07.950
and my parents were like you
cannot, you cannot be gay.

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:10.230
You cannot tell
anyone you're gay.

00:10:10.230 --> 00:10:13.200
They will really, really
have a problem with you.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:15.864
And I was in school, and
I'd been elected head girl,

00:10:15.864 --> 00:10:17.280
and the school
said, actually, you

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:20.880
can't be head girl because
we've got 11-year-olds here.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:22.980
And if they see that
you're head girl,

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:25.950
they might think that your
decisions and choices you make

00:10:25.950 --> 00:10:26.980
are the right ones.

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:28.890
So we're going to make
you deputy head girl,

00:10:28.890 --> 00:10:31.510
because that's the party one.

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:33.680
And, yeah, that seems
really reasonable to me.

00:10:33.680 --> 00:10:34.710
And all I could
hear is my mom going

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:36.300
this is going to get in
your way, get in your way.

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:36.910
And I thought it is.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:37.868
It's getting in my way.

00:10:37.868 --> 00:10:41.290
I've got to be really
careful about this.

00:10:41.290 --> 00:10:44.459
And I did a speech at
school, school's speech day

00:10:44.459 --> 00:10:45.000
or something.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:45.870
And my mom was in the queue.

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:47.703
And the woman in front
said to her daughter,

00:10:47.703 --> 00:10:48.930
Ruth was very good.

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:50.910
She said yeah, she's gay though.

00:10:50.910 --> 00:10:51.640
Oh, it's a shame.

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:55.440
And my mom absolutely
collapsed with anxiety,

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:57.000
and love, and fierceness.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.170
And she didn't know what
to do with that stuff.

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:00.720
And I feel it now.

00:11:00.720 --> 00:11:03.360
So she said you're not
going to get into Oxford.

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:05.940
Whatever you do, don't
let them know you're gay--

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:08.190
and don't-- so I
got into Oxford,

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:11.130
but with that voice ringing in
my ear that I wouldn't be OK.

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:11.910
Don't tell anyone.

00:11:11.910 --> 00:11:13.680
Now, you can't go
to Oxford and not

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:16.560
tell anyone you're gay, because
that would make you different,

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:18.240
because most people
in Oxford are gay.

00:11:18.240 --> 00:11:22.419
So pretty much-- so I
came out straightaway,

00:11:22.419 --> 00:11:24.210
became president of
the junior common room,

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:26.376
and then was elected president
of the student union.

00:11:26.376 --> 00:11:29.610
So at that stage,
was really learning

00:11:29.610 --> 00:11:34.320
how to develop a very strong
narrative about identity,

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:38.460
a real awareness of how fear
gets in the way of you being

00:11:38.460 --> 00:11:41.070
able to be yourself, but also
very aware of how utterly

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:42.030
privileged I was.

00:11:42.030 --> 00:11:47.040
I was smart, educated, white,
had good chat, could work hard,

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:48.400
I knew all those things.

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:50.820
But what I was very aware
of is how deeply unfair

00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:53.670
it is that barriers are
created to people getting on

00:11:53.670 --> 00:11:56.141
through fear, and
through discrimination,

00:11:56.141 --> 00:11:58.140
and through prejudice,
and through, and through,

00:11:58.140 --> 00:11:58.740
and through, and through.

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:00.132
And I'm a good campaigner.

00:12:00.132 --> 00:12:00.840
I'm a campaigner.

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:02.220
That's what I learned at Oxford.

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:04.920
I didn't learn how to translate
streets of Old English,

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:09.030
I barely scraped my T1, but I
did learn I was a campaigner.

00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:11.640
And on that, when
I left university,

00:12:11.640 --> 00:12:14.610
I went and worked in
various different places,

00:12:14.610 --> 00:12:15.270
finding my way.

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:18.120
But at 25, when I was 25,
a job came up in Stonewall.

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:21.510
So I started in Stonewall, baby
dike, number three haircut,

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:23.220
20 Marlboro lights.

00:12:23.220 --> 00:12:26.170
And when I was-- as the
president of course,

00:12:26.170 --> 00:12:28.680
student union president, I got
lots of calls from companies.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:30.240
We're really interested in you.

00:12:30.240 --> 00:12:31.880
I thought you're not.

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:32.630
They never saw me.

00:12:32.630 --> 00:12:33.950
It was pre-internet days.

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:36.120
I mean, they saw my CV,
but they didn't know--

00:12:36.120 --> 00:12:38.130
I thought, if they
knew who I was.

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:40.230
It was that voice of my
mother ringing in my ear,

00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:41.880
you're not going to get on,
you're not going to get a job,

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:44.250
they're not going to like
you, they're not going to--

00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:47.370
I thought I can't work for the
big five or wherever they are.

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:48.690
I can't do that.

00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:50.602
I am not going to be a good fit.

00:12:50.602 --> 00:12:52.060
I did a careers
test, and they said

00:12:52.060 --> 00:12:52.800
you should go for the army.

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:54.357
And I laughed, and
laughed, laughed.

00:12:54.357 --> 00:12:56.940
Now, actually, I'd have probably
been a good fit for the army.

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.695
I mean, the stigmatism and
general day daydreamingness

00:12:59.695 --> 00:13:00.570
wouldn't have helped.

00:13:00.570 --> 00:13:01.800
But I probably would--

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:02.880
I'm a good leader.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:04.890
You know, that might
have been a good option.

00:13:04.890 --> 00:13:07.098
Any of those companies could
have been a good option.

00:13:07.098 --> 00:13:09.850
But I ruled myself out, ruled
myself out, ruled myself out.

00:13:09.850 --> 00:13:12.990
So I started in Stonewall, baby
dike, 25 years old, 25 staff,

00:13:12.990 --> 00:13:14.550
1.4 million at that time.

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:18.400
And Stonewall was
assiduously campaigning for--

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:20.420
what's this counting
down-- oh, no, sorry--

00:13:23.860 --> 00:13:26.520
Stonewall was assiduously
assimilationist.

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:28.370
So Stonewall's campaigning.

00:13:28.370 --> 00:13:30.240
And we are really good at it.

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:33.900
It was all about saying
gay people are normal,

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:35.730
we're just like you.

00:13:35.730 --> 00:13:36.902
We want to pay taxes.

00:13:36.902 --> 00:13:37.860
We want to have babies.

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:39.090
We want to get married.

00:13:39.090 --> 00:13:40.875
Look how sensible
and normal we are.

00:13:40.875 --> 00:13:42.750
We're not going to talk
about sex in toilets.

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:44.580
We're going to talk about love.

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:46.980
We're not going to
talk about complex,

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:49.560
messed up relationships
that everybody has.

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:53.580
We're going to talk about good,
solid, monogamy, and good gays.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:55.080
We're going to talk
about nice gays.

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:57.690
We're going to talk about
the gay men who not too camp.

00:13:57.690 --> 00:14:00.106
We're going to talk about the
women who are not too butch.

00:14:00.106 --> 00:14:05.340
We're going to talk about the
really nice side of being gay.

00:14:05.340 --> 00:14:06.930
And that was the mission.

00:14:06.930 --> 00:14:09.510
The mission was in
every boardroom,

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:13.050
in every institution, gay
people are just like you.

00:14:13.050 --> 00:14:15.427
And I really struggled a bit.

00:14:15.427 --> 00:14:16.260
You know, I really--

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:19.930
I softened up, I wore
blouses, my hair was longer.

00:14:19.930 --> 00:14:22.920
And I thought I'm not going
to get on here, actually.

00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:25.620
I can never be chief executive,
because the politicians

00:14:25.620 --> 00:14:26.520
won't like me enough.

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:28.590
I'm too, I'm too--

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:31.300
I'm not neat enough.

00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:33.220
So ruling myself out
even at that stage,

00:14:33.220 --> 00:14:35.440
in a place where I should
have been most comfortable.

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:38.110
Now history will judge
whether Stonewall

00:14:38.110 --> 00:14:41.560
was right to pursue this kind
of assiduously assimilationist

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:42.460
approach.

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:44.650
We have the best
legislation in relation

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:46.780
to sexual orientation
in the world.

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:48.524
And we got that
because while we were

00:14:48.524 --> 00:14:50.440
changing the law about
lesbians having babies,

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:51.250
they didn't notice.

00:14:51.250 --> 00:14:53.740
Because they just looked this
nice shiny thing over here.

00:14:53.740 --> 00:14:56.680
You know, the polite
courteous approach

00:14:56.680 --> 00:14:58.160
has been really effective.

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:02.170
And as a change agent, I totally
believe that the biggest power

00:15:02.170 --> 00:15:03.500
influence, our employers.

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:06.730
You know, when Barclays puts
MX on their credit cards

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:08.800
to acknowledge
non-binary identities,

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:12.310
that is more powerful than
anything Stonewall can ever do.

00:15:12.310 --> 00:15:16.330
When Accenture
work in the Sudan,

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:17.976
and talk about same
sex relationships,

00:15:17.976 --> 00:15:18.850
that's more powerful.

00:15:18.850 --> 00:15:21.240
You know, all these things,
these power agencies,

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:24.010
these centers of power are
changing and falling away.

00:15:24.010 --> 00:15:25.720
Capitalism is changing.

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:29.320
Social change is at the heart
of any capitalist state movement

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:30.130
right now.

00:15:30.130 --> 00:15:32.920
The need to work with
everyone, and be courteous,

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:35.530
and work well, and match
them, and match their style

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:37.190
is essential.

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:38.620
And I still do that.

00:15:38.620 --> 00:15:42.490
I can move in any
space, in any place.

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:45.460
But what I had to learn when
I became chief executive,

00:15:45.460 --> 00:15:48.019
is that actually we couldn't
leave people behind.

00:15:48.019 --> 00:15:49.810
So I did seven different
jobs in Stonewall.

00:15:49.810 --> 00:15:52.990
And part of my narrative is I'm
very loyal to the institutions

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:53.950
I belong to.

00:15:53.950 --> 00:15:56.380
Oxford University is
absolutely my family.

00:15:56.380 --> 00:15:57.704
Stonewall is my family.

00:15:57.704 --> 00:15:59.620
Quite what I'm going to
do next, I don't know.

00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:01.960
But I know I will need
to belong to something.

00:16:01.960 --> 00:16:03.836
I will need to belong
to an organization that

00:16:03.836 --> 00:16:05.918
feels like that family,
because that's how I work.

00:16:05.918 --> 00:16:06.940
I can't dip in and out.

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:09.070
I have to feel part of it.

00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:14.140
Six jobs-- Stonewall's now 120
staff and 7.5 million turnover.

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:15.730
We take no core
government funding.

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:17.140
We take a bit for projects.

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:18.797
Very diverse income portfolios.

00:16:18.797 --> 00:16:20.380
So being chief
executive of Stonewall,

00:16:20.380 --> 00:16:22.420
I have to be quite shrewd
businesswoman, to be honest.

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:23.961
I have to understand
profit and loss.

00:16:23.961 --> 00:16:26.014
I have to understand
where income comes from,

00:16:26.014 --> 00:16:28.180
and how much we can spend,
and how much we can save.

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:30.130
I have to understand all that.

00:16:30.130 --> 00:16:32.080
And then I have
to be a chief gay.

00:16:32.080 --> 00:16:37.570
And that kind of professional
gay role is quite hard.

00:16:37.570 --> 00:16:39.820
It's quite hard
to juxtapose that

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:42.340
with actually managing
a small enterprise,

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:44.450
with all the things
that come with that.

00:16:44.450 --> 00:16:45.642
And it's a big ask.

00:16:45.642 --> 00:16:47.350
And one of the things
that I was actually

00:16:47.350 --> 00:16:50.260
committed to in 2014 when
I became chief executive

00:16:50.260 --> 00:16:52.510
was quite major cultural change.

00:16:52.510 --> 00:16:54.760
I wanted us to be
able to do both.

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:56.950
I wanted us to be able to
work with the Archbishop

00:16:56.950 --> 00:16:58.060
of Canterbury.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:01.030
My three clients, Archbishop
of Canterbury, Premier League

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:04.220
footballers, and
security services.

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:06.579
You know, my ability to
navigate in those three spaces

00:17:06.579 --> 00:17:09.010
is absolutely crucial to
my ability to do my job.

00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:10.160
I want that.

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:12.032
But I want the
queer non-binary kid

00:17:12.032 --> 00:17:13.990
who's bullied because he
doesn't know what he's

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:16.630
doing to be part of that too.

00:17:16.630 --> 00:17:19.524
So I wanted trans people to
be involved in Stonewall.

00:17:19.524 --> 00:17:20.940
Much of our big
work at the moment

00:17:20.940 --> 00:17:23.109
is around black, Asian,
and minority communities

00:17:23.109 --> 00:17:24.506
coming into Stonewall.

00:17:24.506 --> 00:17:25.880
I want people who
are left behind

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:27.310
to feel part of Stonewall.

00:17:27.310 --> 00:17:29.977
And that require a
significant cultural change.

00:17:29.977 --> 00:17:31.810
And that's where the
stuff got scary for me.

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:35.440
That's where I suddenly
stopped coasting, and was like,

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:38.110
OK, now I'm a little
bit out of my depth.

00:17:38.110 --> 00:17:39.550
How do you do
culture change when

00:17:39.550 --> 00:17:42.190
you've been part of an
institution for that long,

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:44.785
when you've learned to
another CEO for that long?

00:17:44.785 --> 00:17:45.660
How do you challenge?

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:46.999
So this is what I've learned.

00:17:46.999 --> 00:17:49.540
I've learned that people emulate
the style of leadership they

00:17:49.540 --> 00:17:52.420
deem to be successful and
they generally do it badly.

00:17:52.420 --> 00:17:56.080
The whole issue of
inclusion is about people

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:59.410
trying to be something that
they're not all the time.

00:17:59.410 --> 00:18:01.767
Diversity is something
that people obsess about.

00:18:01.767 --> 00:18:03.100
They talk a lot about diversity.

00:18:03.100 --> 00:18:05.080
Diversity should
be your outcome.

00:18:05.080 --> 00:18:06.580
So even in an
organization where you

00:18:06.580 --> 00:18:10.000
have a Benetton advert of staff,
if they are all desperately

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.795
trying to please me, and
act like I want them to act,

00:18:13.795 --> 00:18:16.036
their different
experience is irrelevant.

00:18:16.036 --> 00:18:17.410
So the first thing
I had to do is

00:18:17.410 --> 00:18:21.220
give up power and stop being
a bit of an idiot around that.

00:18:21.220 --> 00:18:24.625
I had to actively bring people
in a room who annoyed me.

00:18:24.625 --> 00:18:26.860
The second thing I
learned, most people

00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:29.930
only like to work with
people who think like them.

00:18:29.930 --> 00:18:32.740
It is deeply frustrating
to work with someone

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:35.489
who doesn't think like you,
who thinks differently,

00:18:35.489 --> 00:18:37.780
who doesn't get it quite as
fast as you'd like them to,

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:38.650
who doesn't keep
up with you, who

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:40.858
doesn't blow smoke up your
ass in the most polite way

00:18:40.858 --> 00:18:41.680
possible.

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:43.431
It is really difficult.

00:18:43.431 --> 00:18:45.430
And I see the army, when
I worked with the army,

00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:46.580
they are working--

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:50.487
they've been six weeks in a
tin can with two other people.

00:18:50.487 --> 00:18:52.570
Of course when there's a
call to go to war in Iraq

00:18:52.570 --> 00:18:53.890
they're going to get
those two people that

00:18:53.890 --> 00:18:56.467
were in a tin can within six
weeks and only talk to them,

00:18:56.467 --> 00:18:59.050
and ignore the trans woman over
there, going, I don't actually

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:00.940
think Iraq can fire
bombs that fast.

00:19:00.940 --> 00:19:01.690
No, no one?

00:19:01.690 --> 00:19:03.040
OK, bye.

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:06.910
We like to draw people
around us who think like us.

00:19:06.910 --> 00:19:09.880
We like to recruit
people who think like us.

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:12.130
And what I realized is what
we were doing at Stonewall

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:14.920
is recruiting in a way that
said look how diverse we are,

00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:17.980
but then making them assimilate
into our way of working,

00:19:17.980 --> 00:19:23.500
make them think, act, and
work as the Stonewall way.

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:24.834
So I had to throw all that away.

00:19:24.834 --> 00:19:26.041
I had to throw all that away.

00:19:26.041 --> 00:19:27.430
I had to do a big
culture change.

00:19:27.430 --> 00:19:28.660
I had to get rid
of lots of staff

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:30.535
without leaving blood
on the floor, which is,

00:19:30.535 --> 00:19:33.330
a bit difficult. All
under scrutiny of a public

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:35.840
who were going well, we're not
ready for a lesbian running

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:37.130
Stonewall, are we?

00:19:37.130 --> 00:19:39.200
And who does she think she is?

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:41.095
And she's not very sociable.

00:19:41.095 --> 00:19:42.590
And she doesn't drink.

00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:45.572
And actually it's gay men
that paid for Stonewall.

00:19:45.572 --> 00:19:47.030
Who the hell does
she think she is?

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:51.077
And that level of scrutiny
is pretty relentless.

00:19:51.077 --> 00:19:53.410
When you are being held to
account on every social media

00:19:53.410 --> 00:19:56.691
platform for everything
you might think or do,

00:19:56.691 --> 00:19:58.690
and you're trying to do
a culture change, that's

00:19:58.690 --> 00:19:59.980
pretty hardcore.

00:19:59.980 --> 00:20:01.470
So that combination--
I was young.

00:20:01.470 --> 00:20:04.060
34, I was too young to be
doing some of this stuff,

00:20:04.060 --> 00:20:06.120
even though I had
all the chatter.

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:07.210
That is quite hardcore.

00:20:07.210 --> 00:20:08.140
So how did I do it?

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:11.890
Well, personally, I
had to really change

00:20:11.890 --> 00:20:13.480
how I thought about things.

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:16.120
I had to accept the things
I wasn't so good at.

00:20:16.120 --> 00:20:18.220
I had to accept that I
needed people around me who

00:20:18.220 --> 00:20:21.770
disagreed with me and
actively make those steps.

00:20:21.770 --> 00:20:23.664
And I had to accept
that sometimes I

00:20:23.664 --> 00:20:26.080
would get things wrong and how
was I going to handle that.

00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:27.670
And I had to make
time for myself.

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:30.490
So I made sure I had all
the things around me,

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:31.510
the staff around me.

00:20:31.510 --> 00:20:33.970
The things I did wrong, I
hired people, wrong people,

00:20:33.970 --> 00:20:34.720
too quickly.

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:37.180
I should have taken longer,
and hired the right people,

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:38.860
and relaxed a bit about it.

00:20:38.860 --> 00:20:40.360
But I had to role
model the behavior

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:41.890
I wanted to see in
Stonewall, which

00:20:41.890 --> 00:20:44.140
means I lead the work on
[INAUDIBLE] inclusion.

00:20:44.140 --> 00:20:46.240
I lead the work on
trans inclusion.

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:48.700
And I make sure that at
every available opportunity

00:20:48.700 --> 00:20:51.410
I'm reiterating our vision,
mission, and values.

00:20:51.410 --> 00:20:53.890
So we've got to a stage is
an organization where we

00:20:53.890 --> 00:20:57.165
feel much richer as a culture.

00:20:57.165 --> 00:20:58.540
But when I look
at organizations,

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:00.190
when I go into
organizations, Stonewall

00:21:00.190 --> 00:21:03.660
works with 750
employers, 2,000 schools.

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:04.660
We're out there.

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:06.030
We're doing lots of things.

00:21:06.030 --> 00:21:10.270
That chat about
diversity is so dull.

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:13.550
Here's our gay member of
staff, he's really happy.

00:21:13.550 --> 00:21:15.730
It's all going really well.

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:18.520
We are fundamentally a
meritocratic organization,

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:21.050
and therefore we don't
need to worry about this.

00:21:21.050 --> 00:21:23.620
So what I just want to finish
on is a note about meritocracy.

00:21:23.620 --> 00:21:25.720
Meritocracy is an
absolute fallacy.

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:28.480
There is no such
thing as meritocracy.

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:30.310
Because meritocracy
presumes that people

