00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:08.120
if we berated everybody every
time someone did something

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:08.620
wrong.

00:35:08.620 --> 00:35:09.922
We'd be in the wrong business.

00:35:09.922 --> 00:35:12.380
You know, the Premier League,
sometimes those conversations

00:35:12.380 --> 00:35:16.559
we have, I do have to
go home and go-- what?

00:35:16.559 --> 00:35:17.934
And the Church of
England, I mean

00:35:17.934 --> 00:35:19.850
it's similar, similar
conversations.

00:35:19.850 --> 00:35:22.430
And you just kind of
have to really just

00:35:22.430 --> 00:35:24.390
be kind to each other, really.

00:35:24.390 --> 00:35:26.180
But see that you have power.

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:28.160
You have power to
change the dynamic,

00:35:28.160 --> 00:35:31.369
and that's what it's
all about really.

00:35:31.369 --> 00:35:33.410
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY: You
mentioned about mistakes,

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:37.430
and I'm pretty sure that we
are having this conversation,

00:35:37.430 --> 00:35:39.170
the awareness is
starting to happen.

00:35:39.170 --> 00:35:41.090
We were chatting about
it at lunch as well,

00:35:41.090 --> 00:35:44.990
using the right pronoun, or
saying the appropriate thing.

00:35:44.990 --> 00:35:49.010
Have any of you ever made
a mistake in a workplace

00:35:49.010 --> 00:35:52.220
where you said the wrong
term, or you weren't sure?

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:54.980
And if you did, what
lesson did you learn?

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:59.170
And how would you tell
others to deal with that?

00:35:59.170 --> 00:36:02.100
LIZ CUNNINGHAM: I
never make mistakes.

00:36:02.100 --> 00:36:06.290
MICK HODGINS: I try to
work out what a pronoun is.

00:36:06.290 --> 00:36:09.130
LIZ CUNNINGHAM: That
was a hard question.

00:36:09.130 --> 00:36:10.690
RUTH HUNT: Yes,
I've made mistakes.

00:36:13.790 --> 00:36:15.130
Stonewall has 120 staff.

00:36:15.130 --> 00:36:15.955
I'm 37.

00:36:15.955 --> 00:36:18.330
That means I'm probably about
twice as old as most people

00:36:18.330 --> 00:36:20.800
there, because we
obviously don't pay enough.

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:22.560
So there's lots
and lots of staff

00:36:22.560 --> 00:36:25.330
who are constantly
exploring identity

00:36:25.330 --> 00:36:28.150
in ways that has not even have
made it onto your internet.

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:29.890
So there's all sorts
of things happening.

00:36:29.890 --> 00:36:32.410
And the odds of me getting
that right every single time

00:36:32.410 --> 00:36:34.600
are pretty slim.

00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:36.920
Non-binary pronouns
are quite complex.

00:36:36.920 --> 00:36:39.760
So for somebody who wants
to get by they add them,

00:36:39.760 --> 00:36:41.920
that confuses my
grammatical lexicon.

00:36:41.920 --> 00:36:44.272
But that doesn't
mean it's not hard

00:36:44.272 --> 00:36:45.480
for me to get my head around.

00:36:45.480 --> 00:36:47.650
I just needed to think
about it for a bit longer,

00:36:47.650 --> 00:36:50.010
and go, OK, that works.

00:36:50.010 --> 00:36:50.950
Where are they going?

00:36:50.950 --> 00:36:52.900
Where have they gone?

00:36:52.900 --> 00:36:54.160
When are they coming back?

00:36:54.160 --> 00:36:56.110
Is as straightforward
as when is she going?

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:57.250
and where is he going?

00:36:57.250 --> 00:36:59.860
But people are very forgiving
if your intentions are good.

00:36:59.860 --> 00:37:02.200
That's why Stonewall has
a philosophy of kind eyes.

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:04.636
And I think the more panic--

00:37:04.636 --> 00:37:06.010
I've just read a
really good book

00:37:06.010 --> 00:37:09.040
called, "Why I Stopped Talking
to White People About Racism".

00:37:09.040 --> 00:37:10.990
And it really
explores-- read it.

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:11.740
It's really slim.

00:37:11.740 --> 00:37:13.120
You can do it really quickly.

00:37:13.120 --> 00:37:15.700
It really talks a lot about
how white people respond

00:37:15.700 --> 00:37:19.150
really guiltily every time
they're racist in some way.

00:37:19.150 --> 00:37:20.509
And it makes it all about them.

00:37:20.509 --> 00:37:22.300
And actually, for
someone who's non-binary,

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:24.820
they don't want it to be all
about you, and your feelings,

00:37:24.820 --> 00:37:26.920
and your anxiety, and
what you've done wrong,

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:28.753
and how that makes you
feel, and whether you

00:37:28.753 --> 00:37:31.120
need to go to HR about it.

00:37:31.120 --> 00:37:33.020
Just apologize and move on.

00:37:33.020 --> 00:37:33.940
And I think that's--

00:37:33.940 --> 00:37:35.710
don't keep doing it.

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:36.510
Be mindful.

00:37:36.510 --> 00:37:39.700
But if you get it wrong,
just apologize and move on.

00:37:39.700 --> 00:37:42.160
MICK HODGINS: Yeah, I agree.

00:37:42.160 --> 00:37:44.500
Anyone who's in
this audience who

00:37:44.500 --> 00:37:48.975
works with me knows
that sometimes when

00:37:48.975 --> 00:37:51.100
you're really, really busy,
you go from one meeting

00:37:51.100 --> 00:37:52.280
to another meeting--

00:37:52.280 --> 00:37:55.300
I only talked about this
recently and people I work

00:37:55.300 --> 00:37:57.440
with have coined
this phrase as drive

00:37:57.440 --> 00:38:01.240
by meetings, where you
arrive in, ask a question,

00:38:01.240 --> 00:38:05.450
answer it yourself, move
on, job done, right?

00:38:05.450 --> 00:38:07.120
And I did a lot of this.

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:09.940
And I'm very personally aware of
how I'm trying to change that.

00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:15.280
So I get it wrong all the
time, I absolutely assure you.

00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:16.780
But I think the
most important thing

00:38:16.780 --> 00:38:19.210
is that we're all human beings.

00:38:19.210 --> 00:38:21.010
I've got a life
outside of Google.

00:38:21.010 --> 00:38:24.150
I've got two kids.

00:38:24.150 --> 00:38:25.150
Things can be stressful.

00:38:25.150 --> 00:38:25.965
We have crazy jobs.

00:38:25.965 --> 00:38:27.340
And you're going
to get it wrong.

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:28.630
You're going to mess it up.

00:38:28.630 --> 00:38:30.490
You're going to make mistakes.

00:38:30.490 --> 00:38:31.900
But I think as
Ruth said, you got

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:34.900
to acknowledge it and put it
right as quickly as you can.

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:37.870
However, you cannot be a
slave to political correctness

00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:38.960
and putting it right.

00:38:38.960 --> 00:38:41.190
That's when it becomes
a real pain in the ass

00:38:41.190 --> 00:38:43.180
and you turn it into
something that it's not.

00:38:43.180 --> 00:38:44.250
RUTH HUNT: And it
makes no difference.

00:38:44.250 --> 00:38:45.640
It doesn't change culture.

00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:46.880
And it doesn't help.

00:38:46.880 --> 00:38:51.300
So it just kind of
reduces all of us.

00:38:51.300 --> 00:38:53.520
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY: And you
mentioned as well in your

00:38:53.520 --> 00:38:56.000
or the majority is women.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:57.790
LIZ CUNNINGHAM: All women.

00:38:57.790 --> 00:39:00.900
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY: I spent two
years working in engineering,

00:39:00.900 --> 00:39:05.190
or hiring for them, and as
all of you probably are aware,

00:39:05.190 --> 00:39:08.380
women are a minority in
the engineering world.

00:39:08.380 --> 00:39:12.960
So you also mentioned that you
have been part of a minority

00:39:12.960 --> 00:39:15.410
group, whether it be your
gender, sexual orientation,

00:39:15.410 --> 00:39:16.290
ethnicity.

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:19.902
How was that experience, and
would you like to share it?

00:39:19.902 --> 00:39:22.110
LIZ CUNNINGHAM: Yeah, so
women make great tax people.

00:39:22.110 --> 00:39:23.380
That's why we've--

00:39:23.380 --> 00:39:27.180
I see some of my team
here, so shout out to them.

00:39:27.180 --> 00:39:28.890
I don't experience it often.

00:39:28.890 --> 00:39:31.660
Or if I do, I sort of--

00:39:31.660 --> 00:39:34.170
we've got a very
technical background.

00:39:34.170 --> 00:39:40.230
And I always revert back to my
core job and my core training.

00:39:40.230 --> 00:39:41.430
So that makes it easy.

00:39:41.430 --> 00:39:44.190
So I kind of go I'm here
not because I'm a woman

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:46.870
or whatever, I'm here
because I'm here to do a job.

00:39:46.870 --> 00:39:50.190
But I wanted to share
one example of where--

00:39:50.190 --> 00:39:52.350
and I think it goes to
your previous question--

00:39:52.350 --> 00:39:54.654
where I made a mistake.

00:39:54.654 --> 00:39:56.070
And I made a mistake
about myself.

00:39:56.070 --> 00:40:00.840
I was on the advanced
leadership lab directors.

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:02.850
You've done that,
Mick, haven't you?

00:40:02.850 --> 00:40:06.540
So we do this scavenger
hunt, but it's

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:10.590
run by a team who trained Nasa,
so it's a serious scavenger

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:11.370
hunt.

00:40:11.370 --> 00:40:14.760
And I was the only
woman in the group.

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:18.500
And it was at a time when Google
was buying a lot of companies.

00:40:18.500 --> 00:40:22.710
So there was a lot of CEOs from
companies that we had acquired,

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:25.050
and a lot of engineers, and
a couple of sales people.

00:40:25.050 --> 00:40:29.132
And I don't know, I
was in a funny space

00:40:29.132 --> 00:40:30.840
because there was
stuff going on at home.

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:31.950
I had to organize--

00:40:31.950 --> 00:40:34.584
I don't know if any, for you
in the audience have children,

00:40:34.584 --> 00:40:36.000
but you know those
Christmas boxes

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:37.977
they do for the [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:37.977 --> 00:40:39.435
So I forgot about
the Christmas box

00:40:39.435 --> 00:40:41.060
and my husband was
in a bit of a panic,

00:40:41.060 --> 00:40:44.587
and I said look, just go and
grab like some of her stuff

00:40:44.587 --> 00:40:45.170
and put it in.

00:40:45.170 --> 00:40:46.300
She's not going to notice.

00:40:46.300 --> 00:40:47.820
She has too much stuff already.

00:40:47.820 --> 00:40:50.820
So some poor child got a lot
of my child's second-hand stuff

00:40:50.820 --> 00:40:51.675
for Christmas.

00:40:51.675 --> 00:40:52.694
But anyway, it's fine.

00:40:52.694 --> 00:40:54.360
So I was in that kind
of funny mind set,

00:40:54.360 --> 00:40:55.859
I didn't listen to
the instructions.

00:40:55.859 --> 00:40:57.300
I was sort of in a funny mood.

00:40:57.300 --> 00:40:59.770
But anyway, to cut
a long story short,

00:40:59.770 --> 00:41:01.690
I literally set myself
up at the bag carrier.

00:41:01.690 --> 00:41:03.690
So everybody had their role.

00:41:03.690 --> 00:41:06.724
So I took the very traditional
female role of well,

00:41:06.724 --> 00:41:08.640
I'll carry the bag, like
literally, physically

00:41:08.640 --> 00:41:09.940
carry the bag.

00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:12.480
And so with had these really
complicated clues to work out.

00:41:12.480 --> 00:41:16.111
And I just didn't do anything
for the first couple of clues.

00:41:16.111 --> 00:41:17.860
And then eventually I
was like, these guys

00:41:17.860 --> 00:41:20.340
actually have no clue
what they're doing.

00:41:20.340 --> 00:41:23.880
So one guy was [INAUDIBLE],, one
guy was doing something else.

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:26.430
And it was all about their
roles and their jobs.

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:28.920
And they were very, very--
and not offending any men

00:41:28.920 --> 00:41:32.250
in the audience, but they were
very clear about their role.

00:41:32.250 --> 00:41:34.590
I made the mistake of
going well, I just work--

00:41:34.590 --> 00:41:37.170
I just take whatever
they don't take.

00:41:37.170 --> 00:41:39.060
And so I really let myself down.

00:41:39.060 --> 00:41:40.920
And so, eventually,
because I've got

00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:44.310
quite a technical
background, I worked out

00:41:44.310 --> 00:41:46.507
that I was actually
working out the clues.

00:41:46.507 --> 00:41:48.090
And so there was one
particular clue--

00:41:48.090 --> 00:41:50.631
and I was so frustrated, because
one of the rules of the game

00:41:50.631 --> 00:41:52.192
was you had to stay together.

00:41:52.192 --> 00:41:54.150
And I was like, I am not
following those idiots

00:41:54.150 --> 00:41:54.840
up that hill.

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:57.152
I am sorry, I'm done.

00:41:57.152 --> 00:41:59.610
So I did a time out with the
facilitator, and I said, look,

00:41:59.610 --> 00:42:02.070
can you somehow intervene here.

00:42:02.070 --> 00:42:04.660
I said, OK, I'll intervene
in this particular case.

00:42:04.660 --> 00:42:08.030
And so they said, look, Liz
is right, you guys are wrong.

00:42:08.030 --> 00:42:10.380
And the clue's across the water.

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:12.330
So we worked out the clue.

00:42:12.330 --> 00:42:13.680
Then four or five clues.

00:42:13.680 --> 00:42:19.890
And eventually, I became the
sort of the clue worker-outer,

00:42:19.890 --> 00:42:21.720
or whatever.

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:26.940
So we won the thing, and we high
fived, and it was all amazing.

00:42:26.940 --> 00:42:31.020
And the facilitator turned
round and said to the guys

00:42:31.020 --> 00:42:34.050
why did it take you so
long to listen to Liz?

00:42:34.050 --> 00:42:37.170
And they were like, well,
we had to wait and see

00:42:37.170 --> 00:42:39.210
how many clues she worked out.

00:42:39.210 --> 00:42:43.650
And then when she worked so
many, we listened to her.

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:46.300
Now, my reaction to
that was, oh, my gosh.

00:42:46.300 --> 00:42:47.520
And they felt really bad.

00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:50.610
They were really torn, and they
said they realized that they

00:42:50.610 --> 00:42:53.825
weren't-- they learned that
maybe they weren't listening

00:42:53.825 --> 00:42:55.200
to their team,
and in particular,

00:42:55.200 --> 00:42:56.680
listening to the
women on their team.

00:42:56.680 --> 00:42:57.840
Now my immediate reaction was--

00:42:57.840 --> 00:42:58.620
I'm not a great listener--

00:42:58.620 --> 00:43:01.161
I was like crap, I'm probably
not listening to people either.

00:43:01.161 --> 00:43:03.840
And now I know what it
feels like to have to--

00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:06.280
taken so long to be listened to.

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:07.752
So there's so many
lessons in that.

00:43:07.752 --> 00:43:09.460
I'm not sure I'm
answering your question.

00:43:09.460 --> 00:43:12.330
But I wanted to make sure to
get that example out there.

00:43:12.330 --> 00:43:15.170
I let myself down as well.

00:43:15.170 --> 00:43:18.240
So I'm not saying that
those men singled me out.

00:43:18.240 --> 00:43:21.150
I think part of the problem
was I set myself up as well.

00:43:21.150 --> 00:43:24.420
I didn't think I was worthy
of having a role on that team,

00:43:24.420 --> 00:43:27.270
for whatever reason, whatever
bias was going on in my head.

00:43:27.270 --> 00:43:29.160
I definitely
contributed to that.

00:43:29.160 --> 00:43:33.890
So anyway that was my
director leadership lab story.

00:43:33.890 --> 00:43:35.760
MICK HODGINS: That was great.

00:43:35.760 --> 00:43:37.740
Note to self, on
the next course,

00:43:37.740 --> 00:43:40.500
find the gay community to
sort out the scavenger hunt.

00:43:43.440 --> 00:43:45.817
I've been lucky
enough, I've worked

00:43:45.817 --> 00:43:48.870
in lots of different countries
during the years, worked

00:43:48.870 --> 00:43:50.590
at different organizations.

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:53.680
Before I joined Google, I
worked for a wines and spirits

00:43:53.680 --> 00:43:56.790
business, a large multinational.

00:43:56.790 --> 00:44:00.310
I spent a bit of time down
in South Africa in Cape Town.

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:03.700
So I joined what was
a pretty early phase

00:44:03.700 --> 00:44:09.600
business, and 100% white male.

00:44:09.600 --> 00:44:11.850
All of them Afrikaans.

00:44:11.850 --> 00:44:15.570
They would speak Afrikaans
first and English second.

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:16.350
It gets better.

00:44:16.350 --> 00:44:19.230
Many of them had fought together
in the South African defense

00:44:19.230 --> 00:44:22.624
forces in the Angolan
war in the 1980s.

00:44:22.624 --> 00:44:24.540
They would barbecue
together and [INAUDIBLE],,

00:44:24.540 --> 00:44:26.130
and hang out together.

00:44:26.130 --> 00:44:29.980
And then this Irish guy, who
was like early to mid-20s,

00:44:29.980 --> 00:44:33.060
arrived down to help
them with their strategy

00:44:33.060 --> 00:44:35.620
and show them how to
grow their business.

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:40.250
So that just didn't really
work out at the start.

00:44:40.250 --> 00:44:44.400
I was a novelty for
maybe about eight weeks.

00:44:44.400 --> 00:44:47.070
There were a lot of,
look, the Irish guy.

00:44:47.070 --> 00:44:49.510
His skin is pale
blue type of jokes.

00:44:49.510 --> 00:44:51.570
And many potato comments.

00:44:51.570 --> 00:44:54.865
And you're in the situation
where you sort of laugh it off.

00:44:54.865 --> 00:44:57.240
But you're thinking, Christ,
this is just not good enough

00:44:57.240 --> 00:44:58.530
for us.

00:44:58.530 --> 00:45:00.030
It was really,
really uncomfortable.

00:45:00.030 --> 00:45:03.780
I would go to social events with
them, and after a few beers,

00:45:03.780 --> 00:45:05.859
they would go back into
their native language.

00:45:05.859 --> 00:45:07.150
And they'd speak for two hours.

00:45:07.150 --> 00:45:09.877
And I'd just be
on the periphery.

00:45:09.877 --> 00:45:11.460
And every time that
there was a laugh,

00:45:11.460 --> 00:45:13.215
you'd sort of feel
the laugh, because you

00:45:13.215 --> 00:45:15.090
didn't know whether or
not they were actually

00:45:15.090 --> 00:45:17.830
cracking a joke about you
or laughing about you.

00:45:17.830 --> 00:45:20.020
So that was really
tough, and not cool.

00:45:20.020 --> 00:45:22.295
I learned a lot from
that experience.

00:45:22.295 --> 00:45:24.420
I think the way I sort of
dealt with that over time

00:45:24.420 --> 00:45:27.690
though was to try and just
get to know people as people,

00:45:27.690 --> 00:45:31.650
and always have your voice
heard, whether or not

00:45:31.650 --> 00:45:33.990
it's in that meeting or
that group environment,

00:45:33.990 --> 00:45:35.704
or whether you can
find a way to get

00:45:35.704 --> 00:45:36.870
your voice heard afterwards.

00:45:36.870 --> 00:45:39.900
Just always make sure
they respect you.

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:41.190
And then the novelty wore off.

00:45:41.190 --> 00:45:42.780
They moved on to
different things.

00:45:42.780 --> 00:45:46.917
Men like shiny stuff, you
know we're very simple beings.

00:45:46.917 --> 00:45:49.250
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY: I believe
at some point in our lives

00:45:49.250 --> 00:45:52.400
we've all been part of a
majority or minority group.

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:54.410
And when we are in
the majority group,

00:45:54.410 --> 00:45:56.870
it is our responsibility
to advocate on

00:45:56.870 --> 00:45:59.820
behalf of those who are
not in the majority.

00:45:59.820 --> 00:46:02.960
So thank you so much for
sharing your examples.

00:46:02.960 --> 00:46:06.020
Ruth, one question that I
would have is obviously,

00:46:06.020 --> 00:46:08.570
as somebody who you said
you are a campaigner,

00:46:08.570 --> 00:46:11.270
and you've done some really
good campaigning for the LGBT

00:46:11.270 --> 00:46:14.900
plus issues, I heard at
Pride this year-- obviously,

00:46:14.900 --> 00:46:17.010
I've been going for the
last three years-- really,

00:46:17.010 --> 00:46:20.060
really good fun, and just
really great to be out there.

00:46:20.060 --> 00:46:21.620
Some of the feedback
that I heard

00:46:21.620 --> 00:46:26.480
was that the LGBT plus community
wasn't very happy about how

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:29.930
the straight people were
taking over and just showing

00:46:29.930 --> 00:46:30.690
their presence.

00:46:30.690 --> 00:46:33.560
So I mean, just from
your point of view,

00:46:33.560 --> 00:46:35.752
is that a valid thing to say?

00:46:35.752 --> 00:46:37.460
RUTH HUNT: No, and to
be honest, as we're

00:46:37.460 --> 00:46:41.140
in this confidential space,
the concern about Pride

00:46:41.140 --> 00:46:42.650
is more than that.

00:46:42.650 --> 00:46:44.420
So what's happening
with pride is

00:46:44.420 --> 00:46:47.990
that lots and lots
of corporates turn up

00:46:47.990 --> 00:46:50.630
to Pride who've never
done any active LGBT work.

00:46:50.630 --> 00:46:54.260
So they hire a van that
cost 30,000 pounds.

00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:58.100
They put 200 people on that
bus who got drunk on champagne,

00:46:58.100 --> 00:47:00.590
quite openly, while the
community groups can barely

00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:03.080
afford to send their
youth group along.

00:47:03.080 --> 00:47:06.750
And it seems like such
a tone deaf PR disaster,

00:47:06.750 --> 00:47:08.900
I don't really understand
why they're struggling.

00:47:08.900 --> 00:47:12.200
Other groups, other companies
who march, who literally walk,

00:47:12.200 --> 00:47:13.640
go down fine.

00:47:13.640 --> 00:47:16.000
Or if you want to go on a
bus, give over half your bus

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:16.940
to a community group.

00:47:16.940 --> 00:47:18.840
In my mind, I think
it's quite simple.

00:47:18.840 --> 00:47:20.950
So what the community is
talking about in terms

00:47:20.950 --> 00:47:23.910
of straight people come
into Pride is about that.

00:47:23.910 --> 00:47:27.256
It's about people
coming on a bus.

00:47:27.256 --> 00:47:28.880
It used to be the
fact that used to get

00:47:28.880 --> 00:47:31.640
shouted and spatted at at
Pride by straight people.

00:47:31.640 --> 00:47:33.980
So now the fact that there
are straight people marching

00:47:33.980 --> 00:47:35.740
and celebrating is great.

00:47:35.740 --> 00:47:39.050
We sponsor UK Black Pride,
which is the next day,

00:47:39.050 --> 00:47:42.980
that has a budget of 7-1/2
grand to the 750,000 of Pride

00:47:42.980 --> 00:47:45.710
in London, and really struggles.

00:47:45.710 --> 00:47:51.000
And the way in which
organizations and companies

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:55.260
work with UK Black Pride,
Pride for LGBT people of color

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:56.400
is really indicative.

00:47:56.400 --> 00:47:58.719
So there's a lot going on,
on lots of different issues.

00:47:58.719 --> 00:48:00.510
But in Stonewall's
view, there are far more

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:02.490
heterosexual people than LGBT.

00:48:02.490 --> 00:48:05.540
Number two, two pints, and
we're all on a journey.

00:48:05.540 --> 00:48:08.189
And the more people
you can get involved--

00:48:08.189 --> 00:48:10.230
the more people you can
get involved, the better,

00:48:10.230 --> 00:48:10.950
to my mind.

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:14.330
And that's always been
how Stonewall's worked.

00:48:14.330 --> 00:48:16.216
Can I just share
a story my sexism?

00:48:16.216 --> 00:48:17.590
I know we're
running out of time.

00:48:17.590 --> 00:48:19.140
So when I took
over as chief exec,

00:48:19.140 --> 00:48:22.500
we had this moment where the
chair, the treasurer, who's

00:48:22.500 --> 00:48:25.080
on our board, and my MD
and me were all women.

00:48:25.080 --> 00:48:29.140
And I said on the board we're
a women's lead organization.

00:48:29.140 --> 00:48:31.830
And one of the men on the
board was so concerned about

00:48:31.830 --> 00:48:35.880
that I had to write a
full paper scrutinizing

00:48:35.880 --> 00:48:40.020
our approach to recruitment, why
I was not demonstrating gender

00:48:40.020 --> 00:48:42.810
bias in any of my
recruitment or restructuring,

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:44.640
how I was going to
ensure that men felt

00:48:44.640 --> 00:48:46.240
able to be themselves
and welcome

00:48:46.240 --> 00:48:49.974
in this new matriarchal
dominant organization

00:48:49.974 --> 00:48:53.820
and give myself
targets around that.

00:48:53.820 --> 00:48:55.950
I had to do this full scrutiny.

00:48:55.950 --> 00:48:59.610
We'd been a male lead
organization for 15 years.

00:48:59.610 --> 00:49:03.440
I had two weeks of a
handover where it was women.

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:07.514
And it absolutely--
it really saddened me.

00:49:07.514 --> 00:49:09.180
And it really frustrated
me, considering

00:49:09.180 --> 00:49:11.910
the amount of sexism
I was getting in the--

00:49:11.910 --> 00:49:14.910
I just thought this is
your moment, trustees,

00:49:14.910 --> 00:49:16.440
to shut up and back up.

00:49:16.440 --> 00:49:19.590
And instead actually you've held
me to account about something

00:49:19.590 --> 00:49:21.220
that is meaningless.

00:49:21.220 --> 00:49:22.350
So there we are.

00:49:22.350 --> 00:49:23.100
That's off record.

00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:23.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:23.890 --> 00:49:25.350
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY: Thank you,
thank you so much for sharing.

00:49:25.350 --> 00:49:26.070
MICK HODGINS: Not anymore.

00:49:26.070 --> 00:49:26.986
RUTH HUNT: No, I know.

00:49:26.986 --> 00:49:27.890
Just--

00:49:27.890 --> 00:49:28.590
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY:
Things are changing.

00:49:28.590 --> 00:49:30.189
Change is what makes
us better, right?

00:49:30.189 --> 00:49:31.230
RUTH HUNT: Yeah, exactly.

00:49:31.230 --> 00:49:32.730
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY:
So, I would like

00:49:32.730 --> 00:49:35.160
to open it to the audience
for some questions.

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:37.920
So please raise your hand and
wait for the mic to get to you.

00:49:41.807 --> 00:49:43.140
AUDIENCE: Yeah, can you hear me?

00:49:43.140 --> 00:49:44.440
Great.

00:49:44.440 --> 00:49:48.110
You talked about the
fallacy of meritocracy,

00:49:48.110 --> 00:49:51.670
and I think here at Google,
while hopefully we're

00:49:51.670 --> 00:49:53.380
very much ahead of
a lot of companies,

00:49:53.380 --> 00:49:56.270
otherwise the world
is in deep trouble,

00:49:56.270 --> 00:50:00.380
we are still deeply
flawed in that sense.

00:50:00.380 --> 00:50:02.360
So you mentioned that
that is a problem.

00:50:02.360 --> 00:50:03.980
But what could be the solution?

00:50:03.980 --> 00:50:06.550
What is the fair way
to evaluate people?

00:50:06.550 --> 00:50:09.640
RUTH HUNT: I think there's macro
and micro responses to that.

00:50:09.640 --> 00:50:11.890
The macro responses to that
are about actually getting

00:50:11.890 --> 00:50:14.410
into your local schools
and helping them improve,

00:50:14.410 --> 00:50:17.837
and helping kids who may not
have those circumstances do

00:50:17.837 --> 00:50:20.170
better, so that when they get
to your recruitment stage,

00:50:20.170 --> 00:50:21.753
they're on a more
level playing field.

00:50:21.753 --> 00:50:23.740
So there's a kind of
macro issue there.

00:50:23.740 --> 00:50:25.770
Looking at degree
programs, entrances,

00:50:25.770 --> 00:50:27.520
making sure that there's
more scholarships

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:29.470
available for young people
going into university.

00:50:29.470 --> 00:50:31.219
Because we've adopted
an American approach

00:50:31.219 --> 00:50:33.280
to higher education,
without any of the packages

00:50:33.280 --> 00:50:34.540
around that to manage that.

00:50:34.540 --> 00:50:37.810
It's a kind of messed up system.

00:50:37.810 --> 00:50:39.460
I think in terms
of recruitment, it

00:50:39.460 --> 00:50:42.680
is about measuring
potential as well as skills.

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:44.230
It's about one on
one interviews,

00:50:44.230 --> 00:50:46.510
repeated, rather than a panel.

00:50:46.510 --> 00:50:49.450
Because panels always reinforce
each other's unconscious bias,

00:50:49.450 --> 00:50:51.700
unconscious bias, continually.

00:50:51.700 --> 00:50:53.920
One on one conversations
make people

00:50:53.920 --> 00:50:56.650
more likely to talk
about their feelings

00:50:56.650 --> 00:50:58.180
and how they're
going to perform.

00:50:58.180 --> 00:51:01.510
But also, it is about
more internal recognition

00:51:01.510 --> 00:51:03.000
that there is
potential in people.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:04.600
So what I often see
in organizations

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:06.308
is that the majority
of [INAUDIBLE] staff

00:51:06.308 --> 00:51:08.380
are entry level
posts, secretarial,

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:09.740
or administrative roles.

00:51:09.740 --> 00:51:12.670
And nobody ever talks to
them about the possibility

00:51:12.670 --> 00:51:14.230
of maybe doing
some in-house work,

00:51:14.230 --> 00:51:15.940
and moving on to something else.

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:17.982
I remember talking to
someone yesterday who said,

00:51:17.982 --> 00:51:20.189
I don't even know what her
educational background is.

00:51:20.189 --> 00:51:21.700
It's like, well
you don't need to.

00:51:21.700 --> 00:51:24.116
She's been a really good
assistant to your team.

00:51:24.116 --> 00:51:25.990
Let's find a way of
actually bringing her in.

00:51:25.990 --> 00:51:28.720
We typecast people
really easily.

00:51:28.720 --> 00:51:30.610
And in something
as big as Google,

00:51:30.610 --> 00:51:33.587
there is enough room to
actually think differently.

00:51:33.587 --> 00:51:35.170
So at Stonewall,
we've actively worked

00:51:35.170 --> 00:51:37.960
with our [INAUDIBLE] staff who
are in more junior positions

00:51:37.960 --> 00:51:40.450
and sent them on more
specific training courses,

00:51:40.450 --> 00:51:42.555
but also made sure
they can shadow me.

00:51:42.555 --> 00:51:44.680
So they've been shadowing
me for a couple of weeks,

00:51:44.680 --> 00:51:46.554
getting access to my
inbox, things like that.

00:51:46.554 --> 00:51:49.750
So really just breaking
down some of those rules

00:51:49.750 --> 00:51:55.049
around some of those things can
be a big help as a sure answer.

00:51:55.049 --> 00:51:57.090
ANAM AKHTAR TREACY: I saw
some hands in the back.

00:51:57.090 --> 00:51:58.260
Do you mind throwing it?

00:52:02.980 --> 00:52:04.730
We all saw the health
and safety video.

00:52:07.320 --> 00:52:09.910
AUDIENCE: Actually, I'll
give it to Philip first.

00:52:09.910 --> 00:52:12.410
AUDIENCE: Hi, Ruth, thank you
very much for coming in today.

00:52:12.410 --> 00:52:14.400
It was a fantastic talk.

00:52:14.400 --> 00:52:17.070
My question is
specifically about what

00:52:17.070 --> 00:52:21.630
is increasingly seeming to
become the silent B in LGBT,

00:52:21.630 --> 00:52:23.100
which is bisexuality.

00:52:23.100 --> 00:52:25.920
So it's obviously quite a hard
thing to represent in media,

00:52:25.920 --> 00:52:28.500
and it's a relatively
hard thing to discuss

00:52:28.500 --> 00:52:32.880
in corporate environments,
because any corporation sort of

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:34.329
wants boxes to put people in.

00:52:34.329 --> 00:52:35.870
And it's much easier
to have straight

00:52:35.870 --> 00:52:38.190
and gay than bisexuality.

00:52:38.190 --> 00:52:39.930
How do we overcome
that as a challenge

00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:41.910
and make sure that
we're putting people,

00:52:41.910 --> 00:52:44.730
if we have to categorize
them, on a scale,

00:52:44.730 --> 00:52:46.590
rather than just in a box.

00:52:46.590 --> 00:52:48.450
RUTH HUNT: So I think
it is that difference

00:52:48.450 --> 00:52:51.180
between scale and a
box is hard for people

00:52:51.180 --> 00:52:53.010
who are new to the journey.

00:52:53.010 --> 00:52:56.850
Stonewall has done bi-only role
model programs, run bi people.

00:52:56.850 --> 00:52:59.190
So we're developing
quite a critical mass

00:52:59.190 --> 00:53:00.960
of people who identify
as bisexual who

00:53:00.960 --> 00:53:04.120
work for corporations, including
men, which is really exciting.

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:06.750
So some of our old bi stuff
was very female dominated

00:53:06.750 --> 00:53:09.120
and heavy, for lots
of different reasons.

00:53:09.120 --> 00:53:11.070
But more men are
getting involved now.

00:53:11.070 --> 00:53:14.070
I do think-- Stonewall changed
its tagline from the lesbian

00:53:14.070 --> 00:53:16.380
and gay charity,
under my predecessor,

00:53:16.380 --> 00:53:18.570
to acceptance without exception.

00:53:18.570 --> 00:53:21.859
So I don't really talk about
words at all like lesbian, gay,

00:53:21.859 --> 00:53:22.650
bisexual, and tran.

00:53:22.650 --> 00:53:24.608
It's all about where are
you at on your journey

00:53:24.608 --> 00:53:25.530
and let's accept you.

00:53:25.530 --> 00:53:28.307
I think that the media really
struggle in terms of bi phobia.

00:53:28.307 --> 00:53:30.390
And I think that there's
a lot to be done in terms

00:53:30.390 --> 00:53:31.830
of challenging bi phobia.

00:53:31.830 --> 00:53:34.080
All our data points show
that bi people experience

00:53:34.080 --> 00:53:37.380
greater incidence of poor
mental health and well-being,

00:53:37.380 --> 00:53:39.640
compared to lesbian and gay men.

00:53:39.640 --> 00:53:42.840
And corporations have been doing
this work for a long time well.

00:53:42.840 --> 00:53:45.180
Gay men are the most
satisfied group,

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:47.970
according to monitoring terms,
compared to any other group.

00:53:47.970 --> 00:53:50.030
And you test it all
down, and then bisexuals

00:53:50.030 --> 00:53:51.030
are at the bottom of it.

00:53:51.030 --> 00:53:54.270
So more bi specific events,
more bi specific conversations,

00:53:54.270 --> 00:53:57.120
more bi role models, encouraging
people to tell their stories

00:53:57.120 --> 00:53:59.400
and their experiences
is really important.

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:00.900
Because young people
are very rarely

00:54:00.900 --> 00:54:02.820
identifying as either
lesbian and gay now.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:04.430
All our youth work--

00:54:04.430 --> 00:54:07.035
I'm a bit old fashioned for
being a standard lesbian.

00:54:09.540 --> 00:54:12.270
So your new recruitment
drive is going

00:54:12.270 --> 00:54:16.200
to be much more bi centered
than lesbian and gay centered.

00:54:16.200 --> 00:54:18.630
So that is going to have to
just shift in time as well.

00:54:21.149 --> 00:54:22.440
MICK HODGINS: Food for thought.

00:54:22.440 --> 00:54:24.685
Just looking to see
where our HR and hiring

00:54:24.685 --> 00:54:25.810
people are in the audience.

00:54:25.810 --> 00:54:26.480
AUDIENCE: Oh, it's not me.

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:28.521
MICK HODGINS: It's
real food for thought.

00:54:28.521 --> 00:54:30.770
AUDIENCE: Ruth, what's one
thing we could all do today

00:54:30.770 --> 00:54:33.770
and when we leave to make sure
we don't leave others behind?

00:54:33.770 --> 00:54:36.430
RUTH HUNT: So find three
people with less power than you

00:54:36.430 --> 00:54:38.000
and go and share.

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:41.210
Because by being in this
room, you have more power.

00:54:41.210 --> 00:54:43.490
By working for Google,
you have more power.

00:54:43.490 --> 00:54:44.720
Go and volunteer.

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:45.890
Go and ask somebody.

00:54:45.890 --> 00:54:48.470
Go and find three junior
people in this organization who

00:54:48.470 --> 00:54:51.230
are feeling a bit lost and
mentor them, and show up,

00:54:51.230 --> 00:54:53.210
and make yourself
available to help them.

00:54:53.210 --> 00:54:55.160
Everybody thinks about
themselves in relation

00:54:55.160 --> 00:54:57.480
to the things that are
going less well for them.

00:54:57.480 --> 00:54:59.181
I think if you start
looking beyond,

00:54:59.181 --> 00:55:00.180
that's really important.

00:55:00.180 --> 00:55:03.980
So I mentor two young
women who are refugees,

00:55:03.980 --> 00:55:05.870
who live in Bethnal
Green, who are just

00:55:05.870 --> 00:55:07.002
trying to do their GCSEs.

00:55:07.002 --> 00:55:08.710
And I meet them once
a month and we talk.

00:55:08.710 --> 00:55:11.690
And I tell them to go along to
meetings at their local labor

00:55:11.690 --> 00:55:12.710
party and get involved.

00:55:12.710 --> 00:55:13.460
It doesn't matter.

00:55:13.460 --> 00:55:15.552
People need to know
the rules of how

00:55:15.552 --> 00:55:16.760
to get involved in something.

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:19.250
People exclude themselves
based on not knowing the rules.

00:55:19.250 --> 00:55:20.750
And I think if you
share your power,

00:55:20.750 --> 00:55:23.150
you can do amazing things.

00:55:23.150 --> 00:55:24.321
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:55:24.321 --> 00:55:26.570
MICK HODGINS: And that fear
