do we behave when we have

00:56:03.960 --> 00:56:08.130
conversations with people who
think completely different,

00:56:08.130 --> 00:56:10.290
who are not so open
minded, who don't--

00:56:10.290 --> 00:56:12.660
because we all come from
different countries and places,

00:56:12.660 --> 00:56:15.060
and it's all great that
we think that we're so

00:56:15.060 --> 00:56:18.250
open minded and Google and
a bunch of other companies.

00:56:18.250 --> 00:56:22.740
But when we go back home or
and we have this really--

00:56:22.740 --> 00:56:26.850
and we talk about what we
talk about here, or like all

00:56:26.850 --> 00:56:30.360
the events we
have, and how do we

00:56:30.360 --> 00:56:33.120
have those hard conversations
when people just start

00:56:33.120 --> 00:56:37.580
making fun of these things, and
just make jokes, in societies

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:40.230
where things are
not open minded,

00:56:40.230 --> 00:56:44.430
and 80% of the population
against all these things?

00:56:47.370 --> 00:56:49.260
RUTH HUNT: So I was
in Poland last week.

00:56:49.260 --> 00:56:52.290
And I don't talk about
the multi nature gender

00:56:52.290 --> 00:56:54.720
identity and the
inclusion of FUCO

00:56:54.720 --> 00:56:56.520
and people's changing
sense of life.

00:56:56.520 --> 00:56:59.220
I talk about human rights,
and I talk about hate crime,

00:56:59.220 --> 00:57:01.240
and I talk about wasted
talent and potential.

00:57:01.240 --> 00:57:03.600
So to a certain extent,
it is about working

00:57:03.600 --> 00:57:05.040
with people where they're at.

00:57:05.040 --> 00:57:07.520
I mean, Premier League, I
don't mention bisexual identity

00:57:07.520 --> 00:57:08.520
with the Premier League.

00:57:08.520 --> 00:57:11.541
I talk about gay footballers
being scared about scoring.

00:57:11.541 --> 00:57:14.040
It is a little bit about making
sure you match your audience

00:57:14.040 --> 00:57:15.166
and then taking it through.

00:57:15.166 --> 00:57:16.915
A lot of the work we're
doing at Stonewall

00:57:16.915 --> 00:57:19.260
is working with Diaspora,
from some of those countries,

00:57:19.260 --> 00:57:22.050
and bringing them together, and
helping them talk about some

00:57:22.050 --> 00:57:25.320
of the ways in which they can
develop new conversations.

00:57:25.320 --> 00:57:28.710
So bringing 36 gay and
straight people from Russia

00:57:28.710 --> 00:57:30.522
into a room, who
now live in Britain,

00:57:30.522 --> 00:57:31.980
is really helping
those people kind

00:57:31.980 --> 00:57:33.370
of talk about these things.

00:57:33.370 --> 00:57:35.370
We did some great work
with teenage girls

00:57:35.370 --> 00:57:37.500
from evangelical
Pentecostal communities,

00:57:37.500 --> 00:57:38.850
who are just awesome.

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:40.170
They're just amazing.

00:57:40.170 --> 00:57:45.390
So really kind of thinking about
what level of empathy exists.

00:57:45.390 --> 00:57:47.940
So we've just come
from Armenia, where

00:57:47.940 --> 00:57:50.970
we've worked with women's
groups on employment rights.

00:57:50.970 --> 00:57:52.680
And then they talk
about LGBT rights.

00:57:52.680 --> 00:57:54.545
But we've gone in
talking about gender.

00:57:54.545 --> 00:57:56.670
We've not talked about
sexual orientation or gender

00:57:56.670 --> 00:57:57.960
identity at all.

00:57:57.960 --> 00:58:02.220
So going at the level that
we're at and accepting that,

00:58:02.220 --> 00:58:03.600
and just doing the best we can.

00:58:03.600 --> 00:58:08.450
Because the last thing that
helps is British and European

00:58:08.450 --> 00:58:12.169
imperialistic lecturing
to other communities.

00:58:12.169 --> 00:58:14.460
And the trouble I have with
the conservative government

00:58:14.460 --> 00:58:16.815
